Family Book Club: Little Darlings by Jacqueline Wilson Dame Jacqueline Wilson has produced a tale of true life grit for the X Factor generation Tears and smiles: Dame Jacqueline Wilson Photo: NAOMI COOPER	By Christopher Middleton 12:10PM GMT 09 Mar 2010
Comments
Our book of the month for March is a tale of two daughters. On the one hand, there's Destiny, who lives in a run-down part of Manchester, with an ailing mother who works around the clock to pay the mortgage. And then there's Sunset, who lives in luxury in Surrey, with her ageing rock star father, her neurotically glamorous mother, plus little sister, Sweetie, and baby brother, Ace.
Although they live worlds apart, the two heroines of Dame Jacqueline Wilson's novel Little Darlings have one thing in common, the same father. For Sunset's celebrity father, the now slightly desperate rocker Danny Kilman, is also Destiny's father, thanks to a brief romance with her mother back in the Nineties.
Not that he has any inkling of this at the start of the book, but by the end of this moving saga – part fable, part satire, part all-too-real-life – the two families have not just met, but collided head-on. Amid the hysteria, the recriminations and the amplified vanity of the adults, the two still-small voices of calm belong to Destiny and Sunset.
It is, of course, a Jacqueline Wilson trademark that instead of getting rid of the grown-ups early on, as other children's writers do, she puts them in the middle of the action. And they don't always come out well. "Because children today don't go out as much in the street to play, they are with their parents more than they used to," she says. "They see them close up and, on occasions, are exposed to the realisation that their mother and father don't always know best."
Just as when poor Sunset hears her father plotting over the phone to run away with his latest illicit girlfriend, and returns to the playroom with the report, "Dad's planning to dump us".
Hardly the fluffy-rabbit stuff of traditional children's books, but Dame Jacqueline stands by her subject matter. "The thing is, every child today knows at least one other child whose parents have split up," she says. "This is a part of children's lives today, and I try and portray what's happening now.
"My view is that a mixed diet of reading is lovely. Children who enjoy my books also tell me they enjoy Harry Potter, for example, and Ballet Shoes: there's room for all stories.
"In this book, for example, children get to imagine what it's like to live both on a rough council estate and in a mansion with a guitar-shaped swimming pool. They are also introduced to the notion that you can have all the money and attention in the world, and still might not be having that jolly a time."
As demonstrated by the world of celebrity in which Sunset and her family are trapped. A world where mother and father hide their tears and unhappiness from the cameras, where the guests at little Sweetie's birthday party are all either child models or the offspring of other artists on her dad's record label, and where the birthday girl isn't allowed to open her presents until the photographer from the glossy magazine has arrived.
"I don't actually know any children of celebrities, but it seems to me they all have extraordinary names and extraordinary lives," says Dame Jacqueline. "Of course, I understand the value of publicity and image, but I am concerned about the way in which young girls are so influenced by looks. Sunset is always being made to feel bad about her crooked teeth by her mother and, as a result, feels very insecure, especially about smiling. By contrast, Destiny has the same teeth, but because her mother has never made an issue about it, she's not in the least bit bothered by them.
"The biggest thing that bothers me about celebrity culture, though, is when I ask children what they want to be, and they reply, 'Rich and famous'.
"If nothing else, I hope this book will plant the idea that if everything in your life becomes public property, the result might be nowhere near as exciting as you might think."
Little Darlings (Random House) is available from Telegraph Books at £11.99 plus £1.25 p&p (0844 871 1515). Find out about Jacqueline Wilson at jacquelinewilson.co.uk The Official Jacqueline Wilson Magazine is published by D C Thomson Reading Notes LITTLE DARLINGS By Jacqueline Wilson
Chapter One
“She feels so skinny, I’m scared of snapping her in half”.
In most children’s stories, the author gets rid of the parents early on; whether it’s Harry Potter or Enid Blyton, mums and dads generally aren’t around to interfere. In this story, though, the grown-ups are around, but it’s the children who are more in control than they are. Which arrangement do you prefer in a story?
“Steve started slapping Mum about”
Destiny and her mum have had it hard. No money, living on a rough estate, taking up with a violent stepdad. A question, then, for parents: do you think this is the sort of thing that should – or shouldn’t - be in a children’s book? Is it right that they find out about the kind of problems other kids have, or is it too early and too depressing for them to be introduced to such things?
Chapter Three
“It’s like Mum has shrunk down into being a little girl, and I’m the grown-up now, left looking after her” She really is a bit daft, isn’t she, Destiny’s mum? Thinking that selfish rock star Danny Kilman is going to be pleased to see her and his secret daughter? A question, this, for the children. then. Can you put yourself into Destiny’s shoes? Can you imagine what it would be like if the tables were turned, and it was you who were more grown-up than your parents? Or have you perhaps had that feeling in real life anyway?
Chapter Four
“Isn’t it lovely here?”
On the face of it, Sunset, Sweetie and Ace have got everything. They live with rich, famous parents in a great, big house with a guitar-shaped swimming pool, they go to a school where there are no rules, they get driven everywhere in chauffeur-driven cars, they’ve got a nanny to look after them round the clock, and they’re always having their photo taken for the glossy magazines. Would you like to be them? If not, why not?
Chapter Five
“Mum has to leave, or she’ll be late for her cleaning job.”
A lot of the time, Destiny’s Mum isn’t at home because she’s out working. So who do you think is the better mother – her or Sunset’s mum Suzy? And why?
Chapter Six
“They are a matching pair, smiling, smiling, smiling, speaking softly in turn – because they are being interviewed.”
Sunset’s parents Suzy and Danny are good at putting on a show of togetherness in public, especially when they’re giving an at-home interview for a showbusiness magazine. Can you imagine living in a house where it’s all about how things look, rather than how they really are? How would it make you feel?
Chapter Eight
“They seem to think they can do anything they want just because they’re so-called celebrities”
So says Claudia; underpaid, overworked, unappreciated nanny to Danny and Suzy’s children. She’s right: celebrities do think they can get away with things that “normal” people can’t. What might be the disadvantages, though?
Chapter Ten
“They’ll be the children of other artistes from Dad’s record label, or any other likely children that Rose-May finds at a model agency”
The guests at Sweetie’s birthday parties aren’t her friends at all! Would you agree to have a birthday party with no real friends, just to get into a glossy magazine?
Chapter Twelve
“When has your father ever done anything for you, Sunset?”
This is a horrible thing for Suzy to say to Sunset, especially as it’s so horribly true. Can you understand the reasons why Suzy is being so cruel?
“This could be huge”
So that’s the reason Danny agrees to welcome his long-lost daughter Destiny back into his life! Because it will be good publicity. It sounds all too likely, doesn’t it? Can you think of anything else that would have persuaded him to accept her?
Chapter Thirteen
How happy an ending?
What do you think about the way the story ends? Would you have liked it if selfish Danny and Suzy had agreed to change their ways, and be better parents? Or do you think that would have been too much like a fairy tale? If this were a film, and we were to see all the characters’ faces at the end, who do you think would be smiling most?
Did you enjoy this book?
If so, you’re in luck – Jacqueline Wilson has written 90 more, for all ages from five upwards. Find out all about her on www.jacquelinewilson.co.uk Book Club
