Moat Brae, a Georgian townhouse outside Dumfries, Scotland, was saved by the Trust within three days of total demolition in 2009, after they managed to buy it from a housing association.
Trustees now hope to re-open it as a children’s literature and visitor centre, with an attic room recreating the children’s nursery exactly as in the story of Peter Pan.
The gardens, where Barrie played while spending five years at school nearby, are set to be reinstated as “Neverland”, with gardens and woods designed to allow children to “play and dream of being part of that magical tale”.
In order to complete the works, the Trust aims to raise £100,000 to complete renovations, and save the damp building from the elements.
They have now offered members of the public a chance to sponsor one of the 39 windows in the property, giving them the opportunity to “have their very own link with Neverland”.
Lumley, who will speak about the project at the Telegraph’s Wigtown Book Festival, said the windows were where JM Barrie dreamt up his most famous tale.
“There’s hardly anyone in the world who didn’t grow up with the world of Peter Pan,” said Lumley. “It’s one of the most famous of all the children’s stories ever written as well as the most enduring; it will never go out of fashion.”
“Windows are terribly important to the story. Peter Pan came in through the windows, and the children followed him out through the windows. It is there that Mrs Darling waited for them to return.
“There is something very special about windows as the link between this world and the magical one of Peter Pan.
“The idea that you can sponsor a window and have your very own link with Neverland is wonderful. At every level, you can contribute to keeping this magical place alive.”
The appeal is part of plans to ensure the house is wind and watertight, with sponsors offered the chance to have a plaque with their names engraved alongside their window.
Prices will range from £500 for a small stairwell skylight, to £20,000 for “Peter Pan’s Window”, situated in what will become the nursery.
Other include the “Starlight Dome” and the “Way to Neverland” window, which will open out into the gardens.
Cathy Agnew, project director for the Peter Pan Moat Brae Trust, said: “We saved Moat Brae House just three days before the bulldozers were due to arrive. A lot of work has already been done but we urgently need £100,000 to restore the 39 windows, which will make the building wind and watertight – securing it for the next chapter in its future.
“Supporting the Windows Appeal is a wonderful way to have an enduring association with J M Barrie and his ‘enchanted land’. We plan to inspire future generations through our recreation of the Never Land, and celebrating great children’s stories.”
Adrian Turpin, director of Wigtown Book Festival, said: “J M Barrie's inspiration for Peter Pan is an exciting and universal slice of such heritage, and we hope the public responds generously to the restoration of Moat Brae House.”
Lumley will be appearing at the Wigtown Book Festival on Saturday, September 28, to speak about the Peter Pan Moat Brae Trust, her life, and her career.
