Danny Care: I learnt my lesson and want my England place back
Harlequins scrum-half has grown up since his fall from grace and is determined to reclaim Test spot for autumn series
Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Mick Cleary
11:00PM BST 04 Oct 2013
Follow Comments
Audition time is coming to a climax, final casting is upon us, the curtain is set to rise. Jostling thoughts in the minds of the England selectors as they approach the autumn Test series will have to become definitive decisions over the next three weeks as the opening match against Australia at Twickenham on Nov 2 rushes into view. There is still scope for a late push into contention, still high-octane matches – think Saracens-Toulouse at Wembley or Top 14 champions Castres at home to Northampton with Ospreys to test the Saints eight days later – for fringe candidates to make their play, games of an intensity that will match what is headed England's way in a month’s time. There is only one area of the field, at prop, that you could regard as nailed on. Alex Corbisiero and Dan Cole, the favoured duo, face each other in the East Midlands derby on Saturday. Even then the credentials of Mako Vunipola, and Joe Marler behind him, should not be discarded. Everywhere else places are up for grabs. Of course, there are back-stories that need hefty consideration. Those who might rush to dispense with Chris Robshaw on the openside take no account of the regard in which Stuart Lancaster holds him for services rendered these past two years. But change there will be. Every other position has new talent clamouring for attention: from Marland Yarde on the wing, through to Joel Tomkins, Kyle Eastmond and Jonathan Joseph in the centre to Billy Vunipola in the middle of the back row. All pushing, all chomping, all looking to make a vivid impression in the weeks ahead. Related Articles
