Such talk is familiar to Danny Care. The Harlequins scrum-half has lived with it ever since Leicester’s Ben Youngs came on to the scene three years ago. As in the era of Matt Dawson, Kyran Bracken and Andy Gomarsall, the No9 shirt has flitted from one to the other. That is not all. You might also add Saracens’ Richard Wigglesworth to the mix as well as the Dickson brothers, Lee at Northampton and Care’s Harlequins’ team-mate, Karl. England are stockpiling talent, finally achieving strength in depth. Care is doing all he can to ensure he runs out against the Wallabies. He has been in a ding-dong battle with Youngs for the shirt. The Leicester scrum-half holds the whip hand as a Lions tourist while Care was rested from England’s tour of Argentina. “I really wanted to go, especially after the disappointment of missing out on the Lions,” Care said. “But the time off has been a real boon. I feel I’ve come back firing and just looking to do what I can for Harlequins and force myself into the reckoning for England.”
Youngs is seen as the more technical all-round scrum-half while the England management has told Care to work on his decision-making. However, he does have pace, that most precious asset. He put it to good effect last Friday against Worcester when streaking clear for a try. “It is all very well seeing a gap, it is quite another thing to be able to take advantage of it,” said Conor O’Shea, Harlequins’ director of rugby. “What Danny brings is special, an X-factor that can turn a game. Too many people focus on the occasional blemish and fail to realise just what dynamism he can bring to a side. “He does manage a game. A scrum-half has to make so many decisions. Every time the ball comes back from the forwards he has to make a call whether to pass, kick, run, pop it up, fire it out. England are blessed with the pool of scrum-halves they have at the moment. There is real quality there. “Danny has got a hell of a lot to offer. He has come back from the summer refreshed, is settled and has a smile on his face. He now looks really ready for the next phase through to the 2015 Rugby World Cup, the most exciting time in prospect for any English player.”
Care intends to take full advantage. He has managed to tread the line between bringing more order to his game while allowing his natural instincts to flourish. “You cannot allow yourself to get inhibited, to worry unduly about making the right decision, you have got to play what is in front of you and back yourself,” said Care. “That is the way it is here at Harlequins. The coaches trust us. You have just got to do your stuff. If it comes off, great. If it doesn’t, you go again.”
Care has lived by that creed. He has been redemption in action over the past 18 months, picking himself up after a self-induced fall from grace when banned from England’s Six Nations squad 18 months ago for drink-related incidents. A potential opponent, Australia’s wild boy, James O’Connor, would do well to follow his example. The Wallabies’ patience with their talented utility back ran out on Thursday when he was banished from their line-up indefinitely after police escorted him from Perth Airport after an alcohol-related row, the latest of several such episodes. The 23-year-old is highly-regarded as a player and would have expected to start against England at Twickenham. Instead he was missing from the Wallaby squad on tour in South Africa and Argentina, and will not be offered another contract with the Australian Rugby Union. Care knows exactly what he is going through. He was dismissed from Stuart Lancaster’s first Six Nations squad in January 2012 yet has returned as a better, more rounded player as well as a more settled individual. “It did me the power of good even though I felt the world was against me at the time,” Care said. “Being banned from your national side is the hardest way to learn a lesson. “And perhaps the best way because it really makes an impact. I didn’t necessarily agree with it 100 per cent yet it brought it home to me when I switched on the television and there were my mates running out in the white shirts and red rose to represent their country. That really hurt. It was a horrible time, yet I had brought it on myself. I had to learn from it. And I did.”
Lancaster, who knew Care better than any other player in the squad having coached him as a teenager, would have preferred not to have been obliged to make an example of him but it certainly brought home to everyone involved in English rugby that a radical shift in behavioural standards was under way. Australia faces the same problem that Lancaster did after the tarnished 2011 World Cup campaign. O’Connor is only one of several Wallabies with disciplinary issues. “It took me time to realise that I was a role model to a lot of people and that if I wasn’t behaving off the field, then I didn’t deserve to be on it in the first place,” Care said. “People make mistakes, especially when young. James is a brilliant player. I’m sure he will learn and be back playing for Australia.”
It did the trick for Care. He intends to make sure that he does not miss out on a Twickenham experience next month. England
